╭─ assistant [MainThread@1167831] ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The previous fix was too restrictive and caused regressions in other tests. The check I added required all PHI nodes in a vectorization candidate group to have the exact same incoming  │
│ value for each predecessor block. This is incorrect, as the incoming values themselves can form a vectorizable group (e.g., adjacent loads).                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The correct approach is to allow different incoming values, but ensure they are handled consistently. The original crash was caused by an invalid shuffle mask being created for PHI     │
│ operands. This happens when the vectorizer gets confused about how to map scalar incoming values to the lanes of the vector PHI's incoming values.                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The `PHIHandler` class is responsible for collecting and organizing the incoming values for a group of PHI nodes. The issue arises when `PHIHandler::buildOperands` is called. It        │
│ iterates through the incoming values of the *first* PHI node (`MainPHI`) and uses its incoming blocks to query the other PHIs. If another PHI node in the group does not have an entry   │
│ for one of `MainPHI`'s incoming blocks, `getIncomingValueForBlock` can return a `nullptr` or an incorrect value, leading to inconsistencies and eventually the crash.                    │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ To fix this, I will add a check within the `case Instruction::PHI:` block in `buildTree_rec`, right before the `PHIHandler` is created. This check will ensure that all PHI nodes in the │
│ candidate group (`VL`) have the same set of incoming basic blocks. If they don't, vectorizing them together is unsafe, so I will abort the vectorization for this group. This is a less  │
│ restrictive and more correct check than my previous attempt.                                                                                                                             │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ sed -i '8439i\                                                                                                                                                                           │
│       for (unsigned i = 1, e = VL.size(); i < e; ++i) {\                                                                                                                                 │
│         if (cast<PHINode>(VL[i])->getNumIncomingValues() != PH->getNumIncomingValues()) {\                                                                                               │
│           LLVM_DEBUG(dbgs() << "SLP: Found PHIs with different number of incoming values.\\n");\                                                                                         │
│           newTreeEntry(VL, std::nullopt, S, UserTreeIdx, ReuseShuffleIndices);\                                                                                                          │
│           return;\                                                                                                                                                                       │
│         }\                                                                                                                                                                               │
│       }\                                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ ' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                                                                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
